 Closer trade ties with Korea favoured 

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Ban ki-Moon (right), Republic of Koreas minister of foreign affairs and trade, and Ficci president Onkar S. Kanwar in New delhi on Monday. (PTI)

 New Delhi, Aug. 1: India and Korea will further explore new investment opportunities in infrastructure, information technology and communication.

 The Korean foreign affairs and trade minister, Ban ki-Moon, who is currently in India on an official tour, met foreign minister Natwar Singh. 

 Both leaders reiterated their stand to strengthen the bilateral trade exploring investment opportunities and co-operations in petrochemicals, textiles, oil and gas field development, automobiles, shipbuilding, steel, pharmaceuticals and agriculture sectors, among others.

 Welcoming the investment of Korean steelmaker Posco in Orissa, the Indian government conveyed that it would extend all requisite support to the Korean firm. 

 The government also invited other Korean companies to invest in infrastructure development projects, such as ports, airports and highways. 




